Project/Translators
-------------------

    Opens a requester which defines the translators used by the
project. A translator is a compiler, assembler or any other program
which @{b}translates@{ub} a source file into an object file. When @{b}TMake@{ub} tries to
compile a source file, it searches through the list of translators to find a
source extension matching the extension of the source file. Once a
source file has been compiled into an object file, the extension of the
object file will be compared with object extension used by the linker.
If the match fails, the object file becomes a source file and the
iteration restarts at the search for a translator. This way you can use
a compiler, which compiles a source file into an assembler file, then
this assembler file will be translated by the assembler and finally
linked by the linker.

    Using the buttons @{b}Add@{ub}, @{b}Delete@{ub}, @{b}Edit@{ub}, @{b}+@{ub}, @{b}-@{ub}, you can add, delete,
modify and reorder the translators. To modify a translator use the @{b}Edit@{ub}
button or double-click on the name of the translator. This will open
the @{b}Translator@{ub} requester.

@{b}Name@{ub}
     Name of the translator.

@{b}Command@{ub}
     Command of the translator.
          e.g. "sc" (for SAS C)

@{b}Debug Opt.@{ub}
@{b}Final Opt.@{ub}
     @{b}Debug Opt.@{ub} are the options used if the @{b}Use Debug Options@{ub} is set in
     the @{"Options" Link "Project-Options"} requester, otherwise @{b}Final Opt.@{ub} will be used.

     The following strings have a special meaning:

    @{b}%src@{ub}
          Name of the source file.

    @{b}%mod@{ub}
          Name of the source file without extension.

    @{b}%base@{ub}
          Name of the source file without extension and path.

    @{b}%obj@{ub}
          Name of the object file.

    @{b}%opt@{ub}
          Local options of the source file.

    @{b}%err@{ub}
          Name of the error file (if not present, then the standard
          output will be used).

     e.g.
          @{b}"-d -o%obj %src" and the source file "text.c"@{ub} becomes
          @{b}-d -otext.o text.c@{ub}.

@{b}Source Ext.@{ub}
     File extension of the source files.

@{b}Object Ext.@{ub}
     File extension of the object files.

@{b}Object Dir.@{ub}
     Directory of the object files.

@{b}Ignore Warnings@{ub}
     If set, ignores all warning messages.

@{b}Check Headers@{ub}
     Option used only for C source files: if set @{b}TMake@{ub} checks for every
     source file if an include file has been modified. If so, it
     compiles the source file. The checking will be done only for
     include files in this format:

          @{b}#include "......"@{ub}
          
          and not for:
          
          @{b}#include <......>@{ub}

@{b}Single Pass@{ub}
     If set, @{b}TMake@{ub} will use only one translator on the source file, and
     will not check if the object file has the extension required by
     the linker.

@{b}Select Converter@{ub}
@{b}Converter@{ub}
     Use these gadgets to select the converter program for the
     compiler/assembler. The purpose of the converter is to translate
     the error messages coming from the compiler/assembler into a format
     readable by the editor. The list gadget displays all converters
     which are available in the directory @{b}TDS:converters@{ub}. If you want to
     use a compiler which doesn't have a converter, you can easily write
     your own one. All the converter has to do is to read from standard
     input the output of the compiler and to write to standard output
     the error messages with the following format:

          MyConverter <compiler_error_file >ted_error_file source_file
          
          @{b}<test.c> 10 2 E <Error Message>@{ub} for an error
          @{b}<test.c> 21 5 W <Error Message>@{ub} for a warning
          
          where
          <test.c>        : source file
          10              : row
          2               : optional column
          E or W          : error or warning
          <Error Message> : error message

     The converter program also receives the name of the source file as
     the first argument on the command line which sometimes is very
     helpful if the compiler didn't write the name of the source file
     in the error messages.


@EndNode

